## 2. Health and Environmental Impacts of Air Pollution

### 2.1 Human Health Consequences

Air pollution is a major cause of premature mortality and morbidity worldwide. The World Health Organization (WHO) estimates that ambient air pollution causes approximately 7 million premature deaths annually, contributing to about one-third of deaths from stroke, chronic respiratory diseases, and lung cancer ([UN Environment Programme, 2022](https://www.unep.org/explore-topics/air)).

Fine particulate matter (PM2.5) is particularly harmful as it penetrates deep into the lungs and bloodstream, increasing risks of ischemic heart disease, stroke, lung cancer, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Vulnerable populations include children, the elderly, and those with pre-existing health conditions.

### 2.2 Environmental and Climate Effects

Air pollution also damages ecosystems through acid rain, eutrophication, and reduced biodiversity. Pollutants such as sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx) contribute to acid deposition, harming forests, freshwater bodies, and agricultural productivity ([European Environment Agency, 2016](https://www.eea.europa.eu/publications/air-pollutants-and-global-effects)).

Moreover, air pollutants like black carbon and tropospheric ozone are short-lived climate forcers that contribute to global warming. Thus, air pollution and climate change are interconnected challenges requiring integrated solutions.

