## 3. Global Trends and Challenges

### 3.1 Emission Patterns and Economic Development

Historically, economic growth has been associated with increased air pollution, following the environmental Kuznets curve hypothesis. However, recent evidence shows that policy interventions, technological advances, and structural economic changes have decoupled emissions from economic growth in many regions ([Amann et al., 2020](https://royalsocietypublishing.org/doi/10.1098/rsta.2019.0331)).

Despite progress in developed countries, many developing regions, especially in Asia and Africa, continue to experience rising emissions and deteriorating air quality due to rapid industrialization, urbanization, and energy consumption.

### 3.2 Policy and Technological Responses

Effective pollution control policies, including emission standards, fuel switching, and energy efficiency, have significantly reduced emissions in some regions. For example, China’s “war on pollution” launched in 2014 has led to a 22% reduction in population-weighted PM2.5 exposure from 2013 to 2015 ([Tilt, 2019](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.envsci.2018.11.020)).

However, challenges remain in implementing and enforcing regulations, especially in regions with weaker institutions and economic constraints. International cooperation, technological innovation, and public engagement are critical to achieving sustainable air quality improvements globally.

